{"type":"message","id":"caf0fff5","parentId":"b2a5d5e5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:04:43.969Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6r0w50gu8j0y_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 110117\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and decide on ONE concrete action to advance the goals.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\r\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n- CFI Analysis is complete (new doc created)\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n\r\nThe most immediate actionable item from the pending list is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would test whether using CFI scores to weight compression provides better next-pulse prediction than simple frequency-based compression.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what this experiment would look like:\r\n1. We need to compare two compression strategies:\r\n   - Frequency baseline: compress based on raw frequency counts\r\n   - CFI-weighted: compress based on CFI * frequency (prioritizing causal invariants)\r\n\r\n2. The test would involve:\r\n   - Taking past pulse data\r\n   - Applying each compression strategy\r\n   - Predicting what the NEXT pulse would contain\r\n   - Comparing prediction accuracy\r\n\r\nLet me design a concrete experiment file for this. I should create a new document that outlines the experimental design and methodology for the CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\nActually, let me first check what data we have available:\r\n- research/CFI_RESULTS.md - has the CFI analysis\r\n- pulse_*.md files - historical pulse data\r\n\r\nThe experiment design should be concrete and implementable. Let me create a spec for the CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that only 5.7% of invariants are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7), while 44.8% are pure noise (CFI=0). This suggests frequency-based compression discards significant signal. A controlled experiment comparing CFI-weighted vs frequency-weighted compression is the logical next step to validate whether causal weighting improves next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a concrete experimental design document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment, specifying methodology, metrics, and implementation approach for comparing prediction quality between the two compression strategies.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n**Status:** Pending\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n\r\nCFI-weighted compression (favoring invariants with high causal stability) will yield better next-pulse prediction accuracy than frequency-weighted compression, because frequency captures persistence duration while CFI captures causal relevance.\r\n\r\n## Experimental Design\r\n\r\n### Two Compression Strategies\r\n\r\n| Strategy | Weight Formula | Interpretation |\r\n|----------|----------------|----------------|\r\n| **Freq-Baseline** | `w(f) = log(f + 1)` | Raw frequency persistence |\r\n| **CFI-Weighted** | `w(f, cfi) = log(f + 1) * cfi` | Frequency × Causal stability |\r\n\r\n### Prediction Task\r\n\r\nGiven compressed representation of pulses [1..N], predict presence/absence of each invariant in pulse N+1.\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n\r\n1. **Precision@K**: Of top-K predicted invariants, fraction actually present\r\n2. **Recall@K**: Of actual invariants in pulse N+1, fraction in top-K predictions\r\n3. **F1@K**: Harmonic mean of Precision@K and Recall@K\r\n4. **Novelty Detection**: Ability to predict NEW invariants (not in previous N pulses)\r\n\r\n### Data Requirements\r\n\r\n- Minimum 10 consecutive pulses for training\r\n- Hold out last 2 pulses for testing\r\n- Compute CFI scores from training set only (avoid leakage)\r\n\r\n## Implementation Steps\r\n\r\n1. [ ] Extract all invariants from pulse history\r\n2. [ ] Compute frequency count for each invariant\r\n3. [ ] Compute CFI score for each invariant (from training pulses only)\r\n4. [ ] Build two compressed representations (Freq vs CFI-Weighted)\r\n5. [ ] Generate predictions for test pulse\r\n6. [ ] Compute metrics for both strategies\r\n7. [ ] Statistical significance test (bootstrap)\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n\r\nCFI-Weighted should outperform Freq-Baseline on:\r\n- Predicting research trajectory invariants (true causal anchors)\r\n- Filtering metaprogramming noise (CFI=0 artifacts)\r\n\r\nFreq-Baseline may outperform on:\r\n- Format invariants (constant across all pulses)\r\n- High-frequency noise patterns\r\n\r\n## Success Criterion\r\n\r\nCFI-Weighted achieves ≥10% improvement in F1@K over Freq-Baseline on research trajectory invariants.\r\n```\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:01:46\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774364683965}}
